1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,376
The strongest positive pattern in the report was iteration and refinement.

2
00:00:04,326 --> 00:00:12,769
Eighty five point seven percent of the sampled conversations built on earlier exchanges instead of accepting one response and moving immediately to a new task.

3
00:00:12,769 --> 00:00:22,317
Those iterative conversations displayed two point six seven additional fluency behaviors on average, compared with one point three three in conversations without iteration.

4
00:00:22,317 --> 00:00:29,500
They were five point six times more likely to question the model's reasoning and four times more likely to identify missing context.

5
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:32,384
Again, association is not causation.

6
00:00:32,384 --> 00:00:38,721
More careful users may naturally write longer conversations, and complex tasks may demand more turns.

7
00:00:38,721 --> 00:00:45,028
Still, iteration gives you a practical structure for doing the evaluation that a polished first answer can suppress.

8
00:00:45,028 --> 00:00:48,750
Treat the first output as a hypothesis and a working draft.

9
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:53,519
Do not restart with a completely new prompt unless the direction is fundamentally wrong.

10
00:00:53,519 --> 00:01:02,394
Point to one claim, one section, or one decision and ask what assumptions support it, what evidence is missing, or what alternative would change the recommendation.

11
00:01:02,394 --> 00:01:04,903
Make each follow-up do a different job.

12
00:01:04,903 --> 00:01:07,317
One turn can clarify the goal.

13
00:01:07,317 --> 00:01:09,971
Another can expose missing context.

14
00:01:09,971 --> 00:01:13,464
A third can test the strongest claim against evidence.

15
00:01:13,464 --> 00:01:16,849
A fourth can compare options under the same criteria.

16
00:01:16,849 --> 00:01:20,653
This creates progress instead of a loop of cosmetic rewrites.

17
00:01:20,653 --> 00:01:28,163
Stop iterating when the acceptance criteria are met, the remaining uncertainty is visible, and the next action belongs outside the chat.

18
00:01:28,163 --> 00:01:31,067
More turns are not automatically more fluent.

19
00:01:31,067 --> 00:01:34,548
The goal is a better decision, not a longer transcript.

20
00:01:34,548 --> 00:01:39,076
First, treat the first response as a starting point instead of a finish line.

21
00:01:39,076 --> 00:01:42,971
Second, give each follow-up one distinct evaluation job.

22
00:01:42,971 --> 00:01:47,759
Third, stop when acceptance criteria and remaining uncertainty are explicit.
